Here's the full migration analysis and replacement code.

## Pattern Classification

| Location | Pattern | Issue on .NET 8 |
|---|---|---|
| `_thread.Interrupt()` | Blocking call interruption | Obsolete (`SYSLIB0046` in .NET 9), unreliable |
| `_thread.Abort()` | Fallback termination | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `_newEvent.WaitOne()` | Blocking call that must be cancellable | Can't be interrupted without cooperative signaling |

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class EventProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly ManualResetEvent _newEvent = new ManualResetEvent(false);
    private readonly Queue<string> _queue = new Queue<string>();
    private readonly object _lock = new object();
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
    private Thread? _thread;

    public void Start()
    {
        _thread = new Thread(RunLoop);
        _thread.Start();
    }

    private void RunLoop()
    {
        var token = _cts.Token;
        var handles = new WaitHandle[] { _newEvent, token.WaitHandle };

        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            // Wakes on either a new item OR cancellation
            int signaled = WaitHandle.WaitAny(handles);
            if (signaled == 1) // token.WaitHandle fired → shutting down
                break;

            _newEvent.Reset();

            // Drain all queued items (fixes pre-existing race where
            // multiple Enqueue calls could coalesce into one signal)
            while (true)
            {
                string? item;
                lock (_lock)
                {
                    if (_queue.Count == 0)
                        break;
                    item = _queue.Dequeue();
                }
                Handle(item);
            }
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        lock (_lock) { _queue.Enqueue(item); }
        _newEvent.Set();
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        _cts.Cancel();           // signals token.WaitHandle → wakes WaitAny
        _thread?.Join(5000);     // wait for graceful exit
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts.Dispose();
        _newEvent.Dispose();
    }

    private void Handle(string item) { /* ... */ }
}
```

## Key Changes Explained

| Before (.NET Framework) | After (.NET 8) | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `while (true)` | `while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)` | Cooperative exit check |
| `_newEvent.WaitOne()` | `WaitHandle.WaitAny(handles)` | Wakes on **either** new work or cancellation |
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | `_cts.Cancel()` | Cancel signals the `WaitHandle`, waking the thread cleanly |
| `Thread.Abort()` fallback | Removed | Cooperative cancellation means `Join` will succeed |

## Pitfalls to Watch

1. **`WaitOne` can't be woken by cancellation alone** — The critical fix is `WaitHandle.WaitAny` with `token.WaitHandle` as a second handle. Without this, the thread stays blocked forever after `Cancel()`.

2. **Signal coalescing bug (pre-existing)** — The original code dequeues one item per signal, but multiple `Enqueue` calls can coalesce into a single `Set`. The migrated version drains the queue to fix this.

3. **`CancellationTokenSource` must be disposed** — It holds internal timer/callback resources. The `IDisposable` implementation ensures cleanup.

4. **Cancellation is not immediate** — If `Handle(item)` is long-running, the thread won't exit until it finishes the current item. If that's a concern, pass the token into `Handle` and check it there.

5. **Don't call `Stop()` then `Start()` again** — `CancellationTokenSource` can't be reset after cancellation. If restart is needed, create a new `CancellationTokenSource` in `Start()`.
